1. Forecasting Lake HURON with ARMA (Direct fit)



  • Recall that Lake Huron data was fit three different way (c.f. Lec 14), each yielding adequate model.

If we treat it as stationary series, we can try to fit ARMA(p,q) series.

  library(forecast)
  source('https://nmimoto.github.io/R/TS-00.txt') 
  
  D <- read.csv("https://nmimoto.github.io/datasets/lake.csv")
  Lake  <- ts(D, start=1875, freq=1)
  length(Lake)
## [1] 97
  plot(Lake, type="o")

  layout(matrix(c(1,2), 1, 2))
  acf(Lake)
  pacf(Lake)

  layout(1)

  Stationarity.tests(Lake)
## Warning in kpss.test(A): p-value smaller than printed p-value
##        KPSS  ADF    PP
## p-val: 0.01 0.24 0.025
  Fit1 <- auto.arima(Lake, d=0, stepwise=FALSE)      # If you force ARMA(p,q) fit
  Fit1    
## Series: Lake 
## ARIMA(1,0,1) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1     ma1    mean
##       0.7665  0.3393  9.1290
## s.e.  0.0773  0.1123  0.3861
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.4784:  log likelihood=-101.09
## AIC=210.18   AICc=210.62   BIC=220.48
  Randomness.tests(Fit1$residuals)

## [1,] 0.963 0.952 0.934 0.567 0.641 0.89 0.684



Model 1 (direct fit)

  • auto.arima() chooses AR(2) with min AICC.

  • AR(2) with constant mean was fit directly to data. With observation \(Y_t\),
    \[ Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} \mu + X_t \\\\ X_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} \phi_1 X_{t-1} + \phi_2 X_{t-2} + e_t \]

  #--- 10-step prediction ---
  plot(forecast(Fit1, 10))

  forecast(Fit1, 10)

  #--- Set options (same as above)
  Y <- Lake                  # Original data
  window.size <- 60         # Window size for estimation
  Arima.order <- c(0,0,2)    # Arima(p,d,q) order
  pred.plot   <- TRUE        # do you want plot at end? 

  # Arima() options: 
  include.mean = TRUE        #
  include.drift = FALSE      #
  lambda   = NULL            # NULL=no transformaton. 0=Log
  xreg     = NULL            # NULL=no xreg.  TRUE=Linear Trend is present
  seasonal = c(0, 0, 0)      # seasonal component

    #--- Use the function

                          include.mean, include.drift, lambda, xreg, seasonal)

2. Foreasting with ARMA with Linear Trend

If we choose that the level is going down linearly, we can try to fit a line with ARMA errors.

  plot(Lake, type="o")                     

  Fit2 <- Arima(Lake, order=c(1,0,1), xreg=time(Lake) )   
  Fit2
## Series: Lake 
## Regression with ARIMA(1,0,1) errors 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1     ma1  intercept     xreg
##       0.6682  0.3817    55.5443  -0.0242
## s.e.  0.0936  0.1136    18.0324   0.0094
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.4612:  log likelihood=-98.66
## AIC=207.33   AICc=207.98   BIC=220.2
  #- plot the regression line
  Reg2 <- lm(Lake~time(Lake))
  plot(Lake)
  abline(Reg2, col="red")



Model 2 (linear trend)

  • Linear trend was fit to \(Y_t\), then the residuals were fitted with ARMA(1,1).

  • Y_t = a+b t + X_t X_t

  • In other words, \[ Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} a + bt + X_t \\\\ X_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} \phi_1 X_{t-1} + e_t + \theta_1 e_{t-1} \]

  #--- 10-step prediction ---
  h=10
  plot(forecast(Fit2, h, xreg=last(time(Lake))+(1:h)/frequency(Lake)))

  forecast(Fit2, h, xreg=last(time(Lake))+(1:h)/frequency(Lake))

3. Forecasting with ARIMA (Random Trend)

Lets look at the difference between the observations: \[ diff(Y) = Y_t - Y_{t-1} \\ \\ \]

  diff.Y <- diff(Lake)      # takes difference between the observations
  plot(diff.Y, type='o')

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2))
  acf(diff.Y)
  pacf(diff.Y)

  layout(1)

  Fit3 <- Arima(Lake, order=c(1,1,2), include.drift=TRUE)   
  Fit3

Comparing MSE

  • From Model1, 2, 3, estimate for \(\sigma^2\) was \(0.4784, \, 0.4612, \, 0.4663\) respectively.

  • Taking square root, that means \(\hat \sigma\) are \(0.6917, \, 0.6791, \, 0.6828\)

  • On the other hand, rolling 1-step prediction rMSE for the three models were \(0.8030, \, 0.7817, \, 0.7781\)

  • Why do they not agree? Which model is fitting the best?

  • What is over-fittting?




4. ARIMA(p,d,q) Modeling Workflow


  • Let \(Y\) be the original time series.


Preliminary Analysis

  • Is \(Y\) stationary? Use Stationarity.tests(). If all three points to stationarity, then set \(d=0\) and perform ARMA(p,q) analysis.

  • If above test is mixed or non-stationary, then take a difference of \(Y\) by diff(Y), and use Stationarity.tests().

  • If Stationarity.tests( diff(Y) ) has all three tests pointing to stationarity, then set \(d=1\), and use auto.arima() on \(Y\).

  • If Stationarity.tests( diff(Y) ) has mixed answer, then you have to perform both \(d=0\) analysis and \(d=1\) analysis.

  • If Stationarity.tests( diff(Y) ) all points to non-stationarity, then you should take difference again by diff(diff(Y)).

(1) d=0 Direct ARMA(p,q)

  • Take no difference. Directly fit ARMA(p,q) with d=0. This is same as ARMA analysis.

  • This model is assuming that \(Y\) is stationary.

(2) d=1 ARIMA with random trend

  • Take difference once then fit ARMA(p,q). Use auto.arima(Y, d=1) with stepwise=FALSE and approximation=FALSE option.

  • This model assumes \(Y\) is not stationary, and either have random trend without drift, random trend with drift, or linear trend.

  • If no drift term is suggested auto.arima(), include it using Arima(), and check for significance.

(3) d=0 Linear Trend + ARMA(p,q)

  • This model is assuming that \(Y\) is not stationary, with linear deterministic trend.

  • Do this if \(Y\) appear to have a linear trend.

  • For thie model to be valid, (2) must have significant drift term

  • If this model is true, then residuals after regression must return stationary series. (Use Reg = lm(Y~time(Y)) and Reg$residuals)

  • Take no difference. Use auto.arima(Y, d=0, xreg=time(y) ) with stepwise=FALSE and approximation=FALSE option.
